This graph implies a positively correlated relationship between bmi and insurance charges. In terms of ethical considerations, I wouldnât consider this a completely ethical way to determine charges, as bmi has been proven to be an often incorrect way to determine someoneâs health.

(ggplot(df, aes(x='smoker', y='charges', fill='smoker'))
 + geom_boxplot()
 + labs(title="Relationship between Smoking and Charges",
        x="Smoker?",
        y="Charges"))

<Figure Size: (640 x 480)>

This boxplot shows that there is a clear relationship between being a smoker and having higher insurance charges. The 3rd quartile for non-smokers is significantly below the 1st quartile of smokers.

(ggplot(df, aes(x='age',y='charges', fill='smoker'))+geom_point()+geom_smooth(method="lm", color="purple"))

<Figure Size: (640 x 480)>

As age increases, the insurance charges increase. This makes sense, because as people age they often have more health ailments. I decided to still break down by smoker because the difference between smokers and non smokers is so significant that my line of best fit was unrealistic for most of the datapoints.

Part 2

X = pd.get_dummies(df[['sex','age','bmi','smoker','region']], drop_first = True)
y = df['charges']

Problem 1

X1 = X[['age']]
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X1,y)
lr = LinearRegression()

my_pipeline1 = Pipeline(
    [('ols',lr)]
)
fitted_pipeline1=my_pipeline1.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_preds1=fitted_pipeline1.predict(X_test)

r1 = r2_score(y_test, y_preds1)
mse1 = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_preds1)

coefficients = fitted_pipeline1.named_steps['ols'].coef_

print("Coefficient Estimates:")
print("Intercept:", fitted_pipeline1.named_steps['ols'].intercept_)
print("Age:", coefficients[0])
print("R squared:")
print(r1)
print("MSE:")
print(mse1)
Coefficient Estimates:
Intercept: 3956.690263404169
Age: 233.76574981435223
R squared:
0.07946942994189099
MSE:
76794719.75205901

The R squared for this model is very low, which makes sense looking at my graph between age and charges - the points are very widely distributed and therefore a simple linear model would not perform well. The coefficients imply that the average charges tarts at $3956, and for every added year you would expect a $233 increase in charges.
